","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7191"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3100"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"3340"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43534"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100098"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with increased effort of breathing over the past three days. He has a medical history of end-stage chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, ischaemic heart disease, hypertension, and atrial fibrillation. His medications include tiotropium inhaler, apixaban, amlodipine and risperidone, which was recently started for agitated behaviour. He resides in a residential care facility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min and irregular, blood pressure 160/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. He is confused and disorientated. There is generalised muscle rigidity and tremor. His skin is flushed and diaphoretic.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start non-invasive ventilation","Administer oral benzodiazepine","Withhold risperidone","Administer intravenous antibiotics","Administer intravenous fluids"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features suggestive of neuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS), a rare but potentially life-threatening reaction to antipsychotic medications. The key features present in this case include fever, muscle rigidity, altered mental status, and autonomic dysfunction (tachycardia, hypertension, tachypnoea, diaphoresis). The patient\u0027s recent use of risperidone, an antipsychotic medication, further supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ewithhold risperidone\u003C/strong\u003E. Immediate cessation of the causative agent is crucial in managing NMS. This is followed by supportive care, including cooling measures, fluid resuscitation, and close monitoring of vital signs and organ function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart non-invasive ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for this patient with end-stage COPD and respiratory distress. However, addressing the likely cause of his acute deterioration (NMS) is more urgent. While respiratory support may be needed, it doesn\u0027t address the underlying cause of his presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister oral benzodiazepine\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in managing muscle rigidity associated with NMS, but it\u0027s not the first-line treatment. Benzodiazepines should be used cautiously in elderly patients with dementia as they may worsen confusion and respiratory depression, particularly in someone with end-stage COPD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered due to the fever, but the clinical picture is more consistent with NMS than an infection. The combination of fever, rigidity, altered mental status, and autonomic instability following recent antipsychotic initiation strongly suggests NMS rather than an infectious process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous fluids\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of supportive care in NMS, but it\u0027s not the most critical first step. Discontinuing the causative agent takes precedence. Fluid therapy is essential to prevent complications from hyperthermia and rhabdomyolysis (muscle breakdown), which can lead to acute kidney injury. Monitoring creatine kinase levels, renal function, and urine output are important aspects of ongoing care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS) is a rare but potentially life-threatening reaction to antipsychotic medications, characterized by fever, muscle rigidity, altered mental status, and autonomic dysfunction.","Immediate discontinuation of the causative agent (typically an antipsychotic) is the first step in managing NMS.","Supportive care, including cooling measures and fluid resuscitation, is crucial in the management of NMS."],"references":["Wang M, Tsai C, Lin CW, Yeh C, Wang Y, Lin H. Association Between Antipsychotic Agents and Risk of Acute Respiratory Failure in Patients With Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. JAMA Psychiatry. 2017;74(3):252\u2013260. doi:10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2016.3793 Available online at : https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2595040","Wijdicks EF, Ropper AH. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome. New England Journal of Medicine. 2024 Sep 26;391(12):1130-8. Available online at ; https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra2404606"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14496"}},"stemMedia":{"da